<h2>What causes ptosis?</h2><p>Ptosis is caused by weakness of the muscle that lifts the upper eyelid. The most common cause in children is an undeveloped muscle (levator palpebrae superioris). Children are usually born with ptosis. In a few cases, ptosis may be caused by an accident or a condition affecting the brain, nerves or muscles. Ptosis can involve one or both eyelids.</p><p>Your doctor may do tests to find out the cause of your child's ptosis or refer your child to specialists for advice.<br/></p>
<figure class="asset-c-80">
<span class="asset-image-title">Eye muscles: Sideview</span>
<picture><source sizes="356px" srcset="/globalassets/assets/illustrations/eye_muscles_side_view_med_ill_en.jpg?format=webp&amp;width=356&amp;quality=60 356w" type="image/webp"/><source sizes="356px" srcset="/globalassets/assets/illustrations/eye_muscles_side_view_med_ill_en.jpg?width=356&amp;quality=60 356w"/><img alt="Medical illustration the levator palpebrae superioris, which is a muscle that extends from behind the eye to the upper eyelid" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="/globalassets/assets/illustrations/eye_muscles_side_view_med_ill_en.jpg?width=356&amp;quality=60" width="356"/></picture>
<figcaption class="asset-image-caption">The levator palpebrae superioris muscle is the muscle responsible for lifting the upper eyelid.</figcaption> </figure> </div>
